#################################################################
#    Annotations
#################################################################

:Applications_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Applications - Downstream system makers and service operators that integrate semiconductors into end-products and platforms—smartphones/PCs, cloud & AI data centers, automobiles, industrial automation, and connected devices. Their product roadmaps and capex set the demand signal for chips across logic, memory, analog, Radio Frequency (RF), power, and optics" .


:Associations_and_Others_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Others - A cross-cutting set of themes that shape disruption and growth across the entire semiconductor supply chain—above any single tier (materials, equipment, fab, OSAT). It consolidates systemic risks and opportunities. The cluster’s purpose is to track leading indicators and translate them into playbooks for mitigation and investment." .


:Components_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Components - Companies that supply non-semiconductor electro-mechanical and passive building blocks used on and around PCBs and within system wiring: passives (capacitors, resistors, inductors); interconnects and electromechanical (gconnectors, sockets, switches, cable/wire harnesses, terminals); EMI/EMC and power components (EMI filters, ferrites, bus bars, power connectors, protection); and related sensors/controls" .


:Customer_Cluster rdfs:comment "A Cluster representing downstream consumers of semiconductor products. Customer_Cluster groups together organisations that integrate semiconductor components into higher-level products or systems. Subclasses include Applications_Cluster, Components_Cluster, and Electronic_Manufacturing_Services_and_Original_Design_Manufacturer_Cluster." .


:Electronic_Manufacturing_Services_and_Original_Design_Manufacturer_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster EMS/ODM - EMS/ODM partners design, source, assemble, and test electronics—from PCBAs and modules to full systems—for brand-name OEMs; EMS focuses on manufacturing/operations, while ODMs additionally own product designs that customers rebrand. These firms drive NPI/DFx, global supply chains, and box-build integration" .


:Equipment_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Equipment - Semiconductor equipment covers the capital tools that make, inspect, assemble, and test chips—lithography scanners, deposition and etch tools, cleaning, metrology & inspection, vacuum/abatement, and automated test systems. These high-value, long-lead assets enable patterning, materials engineering, yield control, and back-end test/packaging across fabs." .


:Fabless_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Fabless - Fabless semiconductor companies design and sell chips while outsourcing wafer fabrication to foundries (e.g., TSMC), letting them focus capital on architecture, IP, and go-to-market instead of owning fabs." .


:Intellectual_Property_and_Electronic_Design_Automation_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster IP/EDA - IP/EDA covers the software and reusable intellectual-property blocks used to design, verify, and  sign off semiconductor devices—spanning logic/physical design, verification, packaging/system simulation, and licensable CPU/GPU/connectivity/security IP that SoC teams integrate to shorten time-to-market" .


:Materials_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Material - In semiconductor manufacturing, “materials” are the ultra-high-purity substances and consumables used to fabricate and package devices (e.g., silicon wafers/substrates, process gases, wet chemicals, photoresists, metals and dielectrics, Chemical Mechanical Planarization slurries, and packaging/encapsulation materials)." .


:Outsourced_Semiconductor_Assembly_and_Test_and_Integrated_Device_Manufacturer_Backend_Cluster rdfs:comment """Cluster OSAT/IDM Backend - Covers assembly, packaging, and final test of chips—everything after wafer fab—spanning wafer bumping/singulation, die attach/wirebond/flip-chip, molding, substrate attach, advanced packaging and system-level/final test. Includes pure-play OSATs that provide outsourced 
services as well as IDMs/foundries with in-house/contracted back-end capacity""" .


:Photonics_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster Photonics - Photonics in semiconductors encompasses integrated photonics and optical interconnects—using silicon, silicon nitride, and III–V compound semiconductor photonic chips such as indium phosphide—with lasers, modulators, detectors, optical digital signal processors, and transceiver modules. These technologies are used for data centers, telecommunications, and sensing." .


:Silicon_Foundry_and_Integrated_Device_Manufacturer_Frontend_Cluster rdfs:comment "Cluster SiFo/IDM Frontend - Covers silicon foundries and integrated device manufacturers from 100 to 300 millimeter wafer process, from front-end transistor formation to back-end interconnect, including lithography, deposition, etching, ion implantation and diffusion, cleaning, and chemical mechanical polishing." .


<http://www.semanticweb.org/schlosseryan/ontologies/2026/2/MarketCapitalizationOntology/Research_&_Development_and_Academia_Cluster> rdfs:comment "Cluster R&D/Academia - Universities and public research organizations that educate talent and run shared cleanrooms, pilot lines, and design ecosystems for semiconductor R&D—often in close partnership with industry. This includes academic nanofabs and mission-driven R&D hubs that provide CAD/PDK access, process labs, and prototyping." .


